content: Worked on Derby Day to solve the startup problem. Turned out that the start button was working, but the S relay was sticking. I sanded the relevant surfaces with fine sandpaper and then readjusted the solenoids until it started reliably. The door button still sticks sometimes, so next that happens somebody should grab the sandpaper again and smooth the button shaft and the hole a bit.

content: Hey there! We discovered some of the wires in this connector were in different spots than they should be. It was blowing a fuse since some pins carrying voltage were instead going to ground. The next step will be moving the 3 wires marked with tape 1 position over to their correct spots, and ensuring their destinations don't have anything blown. This forum post has writing and a picture for the correct sequence
https://pinside.com/pinball/forum/topic/bally-strikes-and-spares-and-star-trek-j3-power-supply-connector
Was it blowing fuse 1 or different fuses?
Fuse 4 if I remember correctly. The 5A one. Different than the one on the original board that was blown
Good note, this was with the new board after replacing it and rewiring the transformer to it
I think this is probably my mistake; I worked on that connector. Was it two wires transposed or something else?
The three wires labeled were all off by one.

This is per the forum post, which we'll double check with our manual before doing the transfer. 

Basically pin 13 should be empty, but our connector has pin 10 empty. So then what should have been 10-12 are located at 11-13 on ours. All The colors are the right order though
That was the broken one, which probably led to some confusion

So it turns out this capacitor was the one that was giving us the runaround. In the meantime, my Hyperball notes from 12/27:
- The problem I started out with was that the ball lift motor was not working. It worked before I moved it.
- I got out the manual and ran through some self-test stuff. Everything worked except the sound and the ball lift motor.
- After some disassembly, I found that the ball lift motor wasn't connected. But where should of it have gone to?
- In the backbox there was a connector of the right shape but the wrong pins were hooked up.
- Tracing the wiring led me to discover that the speaker connector and the ball lift motor had the same connectors. The labeling on them were messy, so I had them hooked up incorrectly. Fortunately, the speaker connector was wired differently, so the speaker was unharmed.
- I hooked them up properly and labeled the motor connections. My label printer worked pretty well for that. I need to experiment more and start a policy of just labeling everything that could be ambiguous.
- Putting it back together went reasonably smoothly. Some of the balls looked a bit grubby, so I polished them all.
- It's now in working order! I played a game and the noise is a bit overwhelming. There are on-line mods for quieting things.
So hopefully the connector just came loose or something.

One way to check the health of a coil is by measuring resistance. Here are a couple of charts:
 *https://flippers.com/coil-resistance.html
* https://pinballmedic.net/coilchart.html

That machine is actually a reskinned 1941 Exhibit Supply Company Sky Blazer: https://www.ipdb.org/machine.cgi?id=2190

If it's actually bad, the best source for old coils is Pinball Resource: https://www.pbresource.com/

If you can't figure out the exact match, you can email them with what details you have and they may be able to name it.

Star Trek update:

Things were done to it this morning; whoever worked on it before me, please chime in. But in the afternoon, I picked up Brian's attempt to figure out why certain lights weren't working. After some investigation, Caleb diagnosed it as oxidized connectors on the lamp driver board, so I cleaned the pins with alcohol and then put the connectors on and off. That eventually got everything going. Then the bonus **8** went out, and it turned out to be the more normal flaky socket failure.

Fussing with that got me to notice that some of the playfield inserts had come unglued, making them no longer level. For the most egregious ones, I used wood glue to put them back in place.

Then I thought, "Ok, I'll play a game and make sure it's ok. But the game wouldn't properly start, and this turned out to be the kickout solenoid not working. So I ran a self test and discovered that the ordering was cuckoo. It would on fire one of the pop bumpers, but it would fire that one twice in a row. The first obvious problem I saw on related boards was that most of the weight of the big wire bundle in the middle was on the top solenoid board connector. And that bundle was all twisted up, causing other problems. So I unplugged a few connectors, rotated the bundle a few times, plugged everything back in, and tucked it into the strain relief loops.

Turning it back on again, it wouldn't boot. The self-test sequence failed at the last step, which the internet says often correlates with a problem with the 43v line. I took a look at the fuses, and one of them, F4, was blown. I double-checked and reseated all the connectors I had moved and tried again. I blew another fuse.

I thought it still might be a mis-placed connector problem, so I got out the wiring chart and verified that the right colors were  in the right places. I also noted that a number of connectors, old and new, didn't have the key holes blocked, so I added those. I also made a quick visual inspection of the solenoids, but didn't see anything amiss. I tried again and blew another fuse. I'm giving up for the night, but I look forward to tackling it next I'm in.
Were we blowing the F4 fuse before? I have a hazy memory of that. Anybody recall why?

I remember f4 blowing, I don't remember why. I think it was blown on the prior board too. I also remember solenoid firing issues where it would do the wrong ones, but it went away mysteriously. I think I recall in test mode is still did the wrong ones, but the solenoid driver board (which is brand new) showed it knew which ones were being fired. That would lead me to believe it's something before that board

Also when I say "mysteriously", it was after lifting and lowering the playfield. So something was jostled, not just like out of thin air

I don't think it is (or at least was) a failed component because of this. Also, the issue wasn't present when we bought it, and appeared after we did some jostling, so maybe there's some loose somethings on the playfield? I made some things. In particular, these are breakers that you can put in while testing so you don't have to blow a bunch of fuses. Some notes:
* There are a variety of different amperages
* For slow blow, use the same amperage
* for fast blow, go a size or two down
* They're in a bin by the fuse pullers on the electronics board
* there are instructions in the bin
* if you trip the breaker, you have to wait ~30 seconds for it to cool down enough to reset
* you can tell it's ready because it clicks

There was a fun problem with Star Trek:
* @Vivian noticed during a play test that some of the pop bumpers were scoring too many points, and in weird amounts.
* I verified that although the right pop bumper scored 100 points consistently, the other two scored more, and not consistently. I suspected something with the switch matrix such that it was "bouncing" such that one hit was multiplied
* This machine has both a diode and a capacitor on those switches (because of the switch matrix). I tested those and they seemed fine, or at least not any different.
* I then hauled out our shiny new oscilloscope to look at the switch matrix signals. They were hard to see, but they all looked the same to me.
* I put it in switch test mode and discovered that if I repeatedly hit the suspicious pop bumpers, switch 21 would occasionally register, which is one of the targets.
* more experimentation suggested that triggering those pop bumpers would often trigger those switches. But there was no switch matrix commonality.
* I looked for obvious electrical problems and found none.
* I disabled those solenoids (by pulling one of the jumpers on the solenoid board), and scoring was normal.
* I triggered the solenoids without triggering the pop bumpers and the problem persisted.
* Suspecting a mechanical issue, I grabbed the butt of a screwdriver and banged real hard on one of the solenoid brackets. This also produced excess points.
* I put paper between the switch contacts for the target. This also solved the problem. This made me pretty sure that it was just an issue of vibration.
* I grabbed one of the leaf switch wrenches and made the switch gaps a bit wider. The problem went away. Victory!

Also, while i was testing this the machine ran out of credits. Although the switch for free play was turned on, it didn't work. Searching, I found that one solution was just to set the replay score real low, so that people got a free game right away, which explains that weird behavior. After a lot of rummaging, it turned out that with the Alltek MPU we're using, it is not sufficient to turn on free play; you must also turn off the credit display, which is a different bank of DIP switches.

So thanks to work from me, Louis, @Vivian,and I think somebody else, Star Trek might be done except for the capacitor swap. But at this point I feel like I'm aboard the Flying Dutchman, cursed to never arrive, so we'll see next week.

There's a new tool in the box of lesser-used tools that I wanted to mention.

The problem: mysterious noises that are hard to find, like buzzes and hums. My prime culprit here is the 1950s machines, which have some loud coils that are hard to track down.

The solution: a directional microphone that you can plug into your phone, meant for use with some application like [Spectroid](https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=org.intoorbit.spectrum&hl=en_US), which shows you a time-series spectrogram. Plug the microphone in, start the app, and wave it around suspect areas, looking for correlations between your mystery sound and the colors of the spectrogram.

The microphone currently lives inside a rounded black soft case inside the box of assorted tools on the right tall shelf. The cable and adapter is in the netting in the case top. Brian, Caleb, and I tried it out yesterday and it seemed to work well enough.

Ok, Flipfix it is! Here's the new URL: https://flipfix.theflip.museum/
For reasons I don't understand that broke the old URL, but the same accounts work, so you'll just have to log in again.

Just to give everybody a quick tour, these are the top-level screens: 
* The first thing is the  [list of machines](https://flipfix.theflip.museum/machines/). It says what condition they're in, where they are, and if there are any open problem reports.
* [A list of reported problems](https://flipfix.theflip.museum/problem-reports/). These could be from users or from us.
* [A list of work log entries](https://flipfix.theflip.museum/logs/). On this screen you can see  every thing we've done, most recent first.

Below that level is basically individual items from those and their connections. If you look at a specific machine you'll be able to see its history of problems and work. If you look at a log entry, you'll see its full details, plus what problem it's connected to (if any).

I encourage people to set this up as an app on your phone (instructions for [Android](https://support.google.com/chrome/answer/15085120?hl=en&co=GENIE.Platform%3DAndroid) and [iOS](https://discussions.apple.com/thread/255899735?sortBy=rank)). That's what I've done and it's very handy.

There are 3 basic ways I expect people to use this:
1. Anybody who's in the game room and notices a problem reports it. We'll have QR codes on all the machines, and we can just open the app. 
2. Volunteers looking for something to do can open up the Problems screen. Step one is just to check it out and see if it's a real problem. They can add a log entry with more description and move on. Or they can jump in and take a swing at fixing it, adding a log entry and perhaps closing the problem report when they're done.
3. For those looking to jump on a machine in the workshop, they can either look at the Machines page (where the ones that are actively being fixed are at the top) or the Log page (to see what's been done lately). They they can do their thing, logging as they go. Once a machine is ready to leave the workshop, they can mark it good and set the new location.

I want to give a huge thanks to Dean Moses for making this happen so well and so quickly. I was going to say that this was already 10 times better than what I would have built. But honestly given how little time I've had for it, it's infinitely better.
So please create yourselves accounts and check it out. Any feedback you have can be posted here.
Oh, and for the nerds among us, the code is here: https://github.com/deanmoses/the_flip
Dean tells me we can just go ahead and change it, which I am excited to try out.
